Aim:
To write a C++ program that demonstrates the use of a friend function.

Algorithm:
Start the program.
Define a class with private data members.
Declare a friend function inside the class.
Define the friend function outside the class to access private data.
Create object and call friend function.
Display results.
End the program.

Program:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Sample {
    int a, b;
public:
    Sample(int x, int y) {
        a = x; 
        b = y;
    }
    friend int add(Sample s);   // friend function
};

int add(Sample s) {
    return s.a + s.b;   // accessing private members
}

int main() {
    Sample obj(10, 20);
    cout << "Sum = " << add(obj);
    return 0;
}

Output:
Sum = 30

Result:
The program successfully demonstrated how friend functions can access private members of a class.
